title: Why Thanksgiving-weekend movies aren't doing well this year
description: Thanksgiving weekend has historically offered a cornucopia of films, letting moviegoers get out of the house and kick back after eating copious amounts of turkey, mashed potatoes and pie.

title: Will Erdogan finally deliver on his vow to invade northern Syria?
description: Turkish President Recep Tayyip Erdogan has in the past week launched a series of airstrikes against Kurdish militants in northern Syria, and is warning that a ground operation will soon follow.

title: Iranian-Kurdish footballer arrested on charges of incitement against the regime
description: An Iranian-Kurdish footballer has been arrested on charges of "incitement against the regime" as Tehran cracks down on anti-government protesters, according to state-aligned news agency Tasim.

title: Rats blamed for eating 500 kilograms of cannabis stored by Indian police
description: Rats in northern India have been accused of eating hundreds of kilograms of cannabis seized from drug dealers and stored in police warehouses.

title: Hong Kong finds 90-year-old cardinal guilty over pro-democracy protest fund
description: A 90-year-old former bishop and outspoken critic of China's ruling Communist Party was found guilty Friday on a charge relating to his role in a relief fund for Hong Kong's pro-democracy protests in 2019.

title: Indonesia needs earthquake-proof houses. Building them is a huge challenge
description: A deadly earthquake that reduced buildings to rubble in West Java, Indonesia has once again exposed the dangers of living in poorly built homes in one of the most seismically active zones on the planet.

title: The US-China chip war is spilling over to Europe
description: Two European chip deals have run into trouble over their links with China, a sign of concern spreading in the West over potential Chinese control of critical infrastructure.

title: Foxconn offers to pay workers to leave its largest iPhone factory after violent protests
description: Foxconn has offered to pay newly recruited workers 10,000 yuan ($1,400) to quit and leave its largest iPhone assembly factory, in an attempt to quell protests that saw hundreds of workers clash with security forces at the facility in central China.
